article.description: Angelina Williams finished one point shy of her career high, scoring 30 points as Illinois upset UCLA (No. 17 EPSN/USA Today, No. 16 AP) 78-63
article.headline: Illini score second upset this season
article.linkText: Illinois shocks UCLA behind Williams' 30 points
article.story:
CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) -- Angelina Williams scored 30 points Sunday to lead Illinois to its second upset of a ranked nonconference opponent this season, a 78-63 win over UCLA (No. 17 EPSN/USA Today, No. 16 AP).

Illinois answered an 8-0 UCLA second-half spurt with a 12-2 run sparked by a Williams 3-pointer, pushing the Illini ahead for good.

"I think we played through our defense tonight," said Williams, whose squad also defeated then-No. 21 Louisiana Tech on Dec. 4. "We just played together as a team. That's what we needed. That's the same attitude we had going into the (Louisiana Tech) game."

Illinois (6-2) gained control of the game by dominating the boards, outrebounding the Bruins 20-10 in the second half and 37-27 for the game.

"They attacked the glass, both on the offensive end and on the rebounding end," Bruins coach Kathy Olivier said. "They did a great job with their athletic ability, just going after the ball."

Nikki Blue led UCLA (6-2) with 17 points and Lisa Willis added 15.

"When you go on the road, you just have a smaller margin of error," Olivier said. "As things were going, Illinois got more and more confidence and once they got that confidence they really attacked."

For Illinois, Danyel Crutcher had 11 rebounds and 12 points on 5-for-5 shooting. The Illini shot 61 percent from the field, their best performance since shooting 60 percent in a March 2002 WNIT victory.

The Bruins had 12 second-chance points off of 10 first-half rebounds but were limited to just four offensive boards after intermission. UCLA shot 41 percent for the game.
